            <article class="prose">
              <h2>What is synthetic division?</h2>
              <p>
                Synthetic division is a shortcut method for dividing a
                polynomial by a linear factor of the form \(x - c\) (or more
                generally \(ax - b\)). It replaces long polynomial division with
                a compact table of numbers and repeated multiply–add steps.
              </p>
              <p>It is especially useful for:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Evaluating a polynomial at a point \(x = c\) (the remainder
                  equals \(f(c)\))
                </li>
                <li>Testing possible roots and factoring polynomials</li>
                <li>Using the Remainder Theorem and Factor Theorem</li>
                <li>
                  Quickly dividing by \(x - c\) when solving higher-degree
                  equations
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How the calculator works</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  You enter the dividend polynomial in standard form (e.g.
                  <code>2x^4 - 3x^3 + 5x - 7</code>).
                </li>
                <li>
                  You choose the divisor type:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <strong>x − c</strong> and enter the value of
                      <code>c</code>, or
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <strong>ax − b</strong> and enter <code>a</code> and
                      <code>b</code> (the calculator uses \(c = b/a\)).
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  The tool:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Parses the polynomial and fills in any missing terms with
                      zero coefficients.
                    </li>
                    <li>Builds the synthetic division table.</li>
                    <li>Computes the quotient and remainder.</li>
                    <li>
                      Shows a full step-by-step explanation and a check of the
                      result.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Step-by-step synthetic division example</h2>
              <p>Divide \(f(x) = 2x^3 - 3x^2 + 4x - 5\) by \(x - 2\).</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Write coefficients and c.</strong><br />
                  Coefficients of \(f(x)\): \(2,\ -3,\ 4,\ -5\).<br />
                  Divisor is \(x - 2\), so \(c = 2\).
                </li>
                <li><strong>Set up the table.</strong></li>
              </ol>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <pre class="mono-input text-sm">
  2   -3    4   -5
c = 2</pre
                >
              </div>
              <ol start="3">
                <li>
                  <strong>Bring down the first coefficient.</strong><br />
                  Bring down 2.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Multiply and add across.</strong>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Multiply \(2 \cdot 2 = 4\), write under −3, add: −3 + 4 =
                      1.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Multiply \(1 \cdot 2 = 2\), write under 4, add: 4 + 2 = 6.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Multiply \(6 \cdot 2 = 12\), write under −5, add: −5 + 12
                      = 7.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <pre class="mono-input text-sm">
      4    2   12
  2   -3    4   -5
  ----------------
  2    1    6    7</pre
                >
              </div>
              <p>The bottom row gives the result:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Quotient coefficients: \(2,\ 1,\ 6\) → \(2x^2 + x + 6\)</li>
                <li>Remainder: \(7\)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>So</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \frac{2x^3 - 3x^2 + 4x - 5}{x - 2} = 2x^2 + x + 6 +
                \frac{7}{x - 2}. \]
              </div>

              <h2>Formulas behind synthetic division</h2>
              <h3>Dividing by \(x - c\)</h3>
              <p>Suppose</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ f(x) = a_n x^n + a_{n-1} x^{n-1} + \dots + a_1 x + a_0 \] \[
                \text{Divide by } x - c. \]
              </div>
              <p>
                The synthetic division algorithm computes numbers \(b_0, b_1,
                \dots, b_{n-1}, r\) such that
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ f(x) = (x - c)\bigl(b_0 x^{n-1} + b_1 x^{n-2} + \dots +
                b_{n-2} x + b_{n-1}\bigr) + r. \]
              </div>
              <p>The recurrence is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ b_0 = a_n \] \[ b_k = a_{n-k} + c \cdot b_{k-1} \quad (k = 1,
                2, \dots, n) \] \[ r = b_n. \]
              </div>

              <h3>Dividing by \(ax - b\)</h3>
              <p>If the divisor is \(ax - b\), we can factor out \(a\):</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ ax - b = a\left(x - \frac{b}{a}\right). \]
              </div>
              <p>
                We perform synthetic division using \(c = \dfrac{b}{a}\). The
                quotient from synthetic division is then divided by \(a\) to get
                the true quotient of the original division. This calculator does
                that adjustment for you automatically.
              </p>

              <h2>Common mistakes and tips</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Forgetting missing terms.</strong> Always include zero
                  coefficients for missing powers of \(x\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Wrong sign for c.</strong> For divisor \(x - c\), use
                  \(+c\). For \(x + 3\), rewrite as \(x - (-3)\) so \(c = -3\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Divisor not linear.</strong> Synthetic division in
                  this form only works for linear divisors. For quadratic or
                  higher, use long division.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check with substitution.</strong> The remainder should
                  equal \(f(c)\). You can quickly verify with a calculator.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>What is synthetic division used for?</h3>
              <p>
                Synthetic division is used to divide a polynomial by a linear
                factor, test candidate roots, factor polynomials, and evaluate
                \(f(c)\) efficiently. It is a standard tool in algebra,
                precalculus, and calculus.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can I use synthetic division for \(x^2 + 1\) or other non-linear
                divisors?
              </h3>
              <p>
                No. The standard synthetic division algorithm only works when
                the divisor is linear (degree 1). For divisors like \(x^2 + 1\),
                you must use polynomial long division or more advanced
                generalized methods.
              </p>

              <h3>Why does the last number equal \(f(c)\)?</h3>
              <p>
                This is the <strong>Remainder Theorem</strong>: when a
                polynomial \(f(x)\) is divided by \(x - c\), the remainder is
                \(f(c)\). Synthetic division is just a fast way to compute that
                remainder and the quotient at the same time.
              </p>
